<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Culture, Media and Sport Committee</title></head><body><div><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Magdalen</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> Wiley</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> [FBB0044]</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Politics Undergraduate Student at the University of Sheffield</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">How well has the BBC performed in the current Charter period in achieving its </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">mission and public purposes?</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">This submission look</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> at the performance of the BBC in achieving its mission and public purposes with regards to young people. My focus will </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">primarily  be</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> on the television channel BBC Three, as it is one of the largest mediums</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> through which the BBC aims to target a younger audience.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">BBC Three was launched in 2003 with </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a  remit</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">bring younger audiences to high quality public service broadcasting,  through a mixed-genre schedule of innovative UK content featuring new UK talent</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. The channel should use the full range of digital platforms to deliver its content and to build an interactive relationship with its audience.’ </span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Younger audiences in this context are viewed by the BBC as 16-34 year olds, a group the BBC have traditionally</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> had problems attracting. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">I will put forward the case in this submission, that though BBC Three has produced some high quality programmes it fails to meaningfully promote education and learning.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> This  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">should be </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> an especially important focus for the chann</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">el as it is aimed at a younger audiences who watch on average two hours of television a day and are particularly susce</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ptible to television’s content</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Therefore </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">for the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">future,  this submission recommends that BBC Three must  put more of an emphasis on educ</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">ating it’s viewers  with an increase in quality culture, arts and current affairs shows. It also needs to make a serious effort to provide </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">positive </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> role</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> models in its programmes rather than negative and stereotypical portrayals of young people as can be s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">een in many of its entertainment programmes. Only then can it be said that the channel fulfils the BBC’s public </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">purpose</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> of ‘promoting education and learning’.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">BBC Three was a particular attempt by the BBC of attracting a specifically younger </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">audience  in</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a way that BBC One and BBC Two had not. This in itself was a positive step by the organisation in targeting a group whose civic participation levels were in decline. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Though this submission may seem mostly critical in nature</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">BBC Three </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">has  produced</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  a num</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ber of programmes of quality which have met its remit for young</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">er</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> audiences. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Such programmes as </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Gavin &amp; Stacey</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Being Human</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> have deserved their critical success due </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to  the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> originality and quality of their content. ‘The Revolution Will Be Televised’</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> successfully combines comedy and current affairs, working both as an entertainment and educative piece of programming. BBC </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Three  therefore</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> has proved  that on some occasions it can fulfil its public purpose of promoting education and learning whilst keep</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ing the content appropriate for younger viewers.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">It must be noted that the BBC’s depiction of young people is on the whole negative and stereotypical. Currently televised programmes such as ‘Snow, Sex and Suspicious Parents’ portray younger people as irres</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ponsible, selfish and only intent on ‘having a good time’.  This programme in particular, where teenagers are secretly watched by their parents whilst embarking on their first </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">holiday  alone</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> consistently depicts teenagers in the different stages of intoxic</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ation, for the entertainment of its viewers. By portraying teenagers in such a way it does little to dispel stereotypes of this age group.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Programmes such as Snow, Sex and Suspicious Parents’ which involve young people binge drinking are particularly worry</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ing as they tend to normalise alcohol as a key part of young people’s lives. A 2011 </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Rowntree</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">report  stated</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> that young people find alcohol is over represented in television, and that a balance needs to be found between portraying the positive and negative </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">consequences of alcohol consumption.  Furthermore, the report found that television can help set ‘healthy</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">’ norms for drinking behaviour.</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Therefore, BBC Three </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">needs  to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> make more effort  to promote and depict healthy attitudes to drinking rather than depic</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ting binge drinking as a norm of youth culture.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">As well as often depicting younger</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> people in stereotypical ways, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">one programme in particular, ‘</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Snog</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, Marry, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Avoid’  is</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> blatantly sexist. The reality programme, which is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">one  of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the channel's  highest rated pr</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ogrammes, is a ‘make-under’ show predominantly featuring women . In the programme a random group of men are asked whether they would ‘</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">snog</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, marry or avoid’ the participants on the basis of their appearance. The men predictably respond that they would avoid</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> them and then a make-over is conducted and men predictably respond saying they would wish to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">snog</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> or marry them. By reducing the women’s self- worth to what other people think of their physical appearance the BBC is promoting sexism, something which any b</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">roadcasting channel, especially a license fee funded one , should be actively trying to campaign against, not promote. The fact that this television show has now had six series also brings with it the more worrying concern that the channel is doing little </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to monitor its content. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In essence, e</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">thics should not be traded for ratings.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">BBC Three has made some effort in providing more educational and document</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ary style programming. However </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">again</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in trying to attract a younger audience, it relies more on shock and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> entertainment tactics. A 2009, BBC service review of younger audiences supports this, finding that those who were part of qualitative research on the channel found that ‘factual content on the channel was not hard-hitting enough and was too close to being</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> ‘light entertainment’. </span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">To look at an example,  the documentary ‘Unsafe Sex in the City’ which follows young people attending sexual health clinics is again more intent on portraying th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e ignorance of the participants</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> rather than educating its viewers on the importance of sexual health. The aim of the programme is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">obviously  to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> laugh at the stupidity of its participants, again doing nothing to dispel stereotypes of younger people. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">As a recommendation for the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">future ,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">BBC Three  needs to make a more substantive effort to provide better role models for its young people in its programming. More emphasis needs to be put on depicting young people’s achievements rather than their failings. For example, ‘Hotel of Mum and Dad’</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and ‘Young, Dumb and Living off Mum’ have provided portrayals of young people moving into adulthood with few basic life </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">skills .</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> This has </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">been  for</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the viewer’s entertainment ,but no programmes have been offered by the channel that portray young people as</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> successfully making the transition to adulthood.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Also as a channel that’s primary audience is young people, more emphasis needs to be put on current affairs that affect young people, for example the struggles younger people now face in light of the rise i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">n tuition fees, cuts in the welfare system and the difficulties of gaining employment.  At the moment BBC Three is only in agreement to broadcast a minimum of 15 hours of new current affairs programming a year. This is justified by saying that</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> this is far </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">more </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">than </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> other</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> channels  aimed at younger audiences </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">which </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">do </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">not broadcast any.</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> In my opinion, this is not a reasonable explanation for such little current </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">affairs  content</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. This works on the assumption that current affairs is of less interest and i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s le</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ss relevant to young people and  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">contributes  to the decline in civic participation of young people. BBC Three as a channel that prides itself on having content</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> of relevance to young people</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, could be the perfect platform for facilitating</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> an increase in cur</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rent affairs </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">prog</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rammes aimed at young</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">er</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> audiences and  subsequently raising interest and awareness of young people</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> about</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> current affairs.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">BBC Three in 2012/13 </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">had  an</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> annual service budget of £121.7million.</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> This large budget is not reflected in the quali</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ty of its content.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Whilst I believe the BBC should continue to be license fee funded, in the case of BBC Three</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the license fee payer</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> is</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> not receiving value for money. Channel 4 has a far smaller budget for its own youth orientated </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">channel </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,E4</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> yet  it reac</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">hes a larger share of younger audiences. Whilst in 2007 core Channel 4 reache</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">d over 80% of 16-34 year olds</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, BBC Three only reached 50% of this audience.</span><a name="_ftnref7"></a><a href="#_ftn7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> BBC Three therefore is not succeeding in terms of either value for money or in competition with other </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">youth orientated television channels.  As a license fee payer funded channel, BBC Three must make serious efforts to address its issues with reaching younger audiences. Its budget should be reduced as it is not money that will improve BBC Three’s success b</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ut more creative ways of representing and educating young people. I would recommend that unless the channel can make significant improvements within the next few years, i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">t should no longer be continued.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">BBC Three currently puts too much emphasis on “risk t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">aking” and it is yet to find a balance between informing, educating and entertaining. Too much viewing time is given to entertainment programmes </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">which </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in some cases give damaging stereotypical portrayals of young people. As a license fee funded channel</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> BB</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">C Three must take more responsibility for creating programmes that are entertaining but provide a more </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">varied  and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> less clichéd view of “youth culture”. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> For now, I think the channel should continue to be license fee payer funded, not as a result of the qu</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ality of the channel as it stands but as it a non-commercially funded channel it has the potential to provide</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> programmes that are of real relevance to younger audiences. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">As previous critics of the channel have noted</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,  just</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> because the channel is aimed at </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">young people it does not mean its programmes have to be of less quality</span><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> or depict </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> young people</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">negatively </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and this is why I urge the committee to take these recommendations on board.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">December 2013</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> BBC Three Programme Policy, 2009/2010</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> Statistic taken from </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">Thinkbox</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">Joseph </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">Rowntree</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> Foundation r</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">eport: Young peo</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">ple, alcohol and the media, 2011.</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-heig